# Canvas OAuth and Release

- Expose an honest integration status before listing/importing: local synthetic demo, not configured, or approved live connection.
- Local demo import must be visibly synthetic, make no Canvas request, and persist no OAuth token.
- Use institutionally scoped OAuth. Encrypt refresh tokens; keep access tokens memory-only.
- Pin/allow-list the Canvas base URL and request only documented endpoint scopes.
- Respect pagination and throttling headers with bounded backoff.
- Instructors and TAs may explicitly import after configuration; only instructors/admins may configure the connection or mutate/approve rubrics.
- Import reads selected Canvas data into local writing records and is idempotent by assignment/student/attempt. It must not write grades, comments, files, or rubrics to Canvas.
- Always provide a release preview and require an approved feedback revision.
- Upload the comment file first, then submit grade, rubric assessment, comment, and file ID together.
- Persist a payload fingerprint and returned Canvas identifiers.
- On timeout, reconcile the current submission/comments before retrying; never blindly duplicate a comment.
- Mock Canvas adapters must be visibly identified and must not be described as production connectivity.
